      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "CFD solver must have documented version control, regression testing, and release notes consistent with MRL 2 requirements.",
      "rationale": "ANSYS Fluent 19.2 was used with documented version control and release validation reports. Solver regression tests confirm numerical correctness for rotating machinery applications. MRL 2 requirement of level 1 is satisfied."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Numerical code verification",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 1,
      "achievedLevel": 1,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Solver must demonstrate verified implementation of governing equations through benchmark problems documented by the code developer.",
      "rationale": "ANSYS Fluent provides published verification benchmarks for incompressible Navier-Stokes and rotating reference frame formulations. Developer-supplied verification suite covers all equation sets used in this model."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Discretization error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Grid convergence index (GCI) must be reported for velocity and shear stress quantities of interest; GCI < 5% on fine grid.",
      "rationale": "Three-level mesh refinement study conducted on the FDA generic centrifugal pump geometry. GCI for area-averaged wall shear stress was 3.2% and for outlet velocity profile was 2.8% on the fine mesh (12.4M cells). Richardson extrapolation confirms monotonic convergence. Discretization error is within acceptable bounds for MRL 2."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Experimental test conditions used for validation must match simulated boundary conditions within documented tolerances; flow rate ±5%, rotational speed ±2%.",
      "rationale": "FDA benchmark experimental data collected at 2500 RPM and 5 flow rates (2.5–7.5 L/min). CFD boundary conditions set to match measured inlet flow rates and outlet pressure within stated tolerances. Temperature and fluid viscosity matched to blood analog (glycerol-water 36% w/w at 22°C)."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Predicted hemolysis index (IH) must agree with experimental measurements within 15% across all 5 operating points.",
      "rationale": "Predicted normalized index of hemolysis (NIH) compared against FDA experimental measurements at all 5 operating points. Mean absolute percentage error was 9.4% with maximum deviation of 13.7% at the highest flow rate condition. All points within the 15% acceptance threshold. Relative hemolysis index RH < 1 confirmed for worst-case condition."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "QoIs used in validation (NIH, wall shear stress, velocity profiles) must be directly relevant to the COU decision quantity (worst-case hemolysis identification).",
      "rationale": "The normalized index of hemolysis is the primary regulatory quantity for blood-contacting device assessment. Wall shear stress and exposure time are the mechanistic drivers of the power-law hemolysis model. QoIs are directly traceable to the COU decision criterion (RH < 1 relative to predicate device)."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Validation must be performed on the same device geometry class (centrifugal blood pump) under operating conditions spanning the COU envelope.",
      "rationale": "Validation performed on the FDA generic centrifugal pump geometry, which is the same device class as the CPB pump under assessment. Operating envelope (2500–3500 RPM, 2.5–7.5 L/min) spans the COU conditions. Validation hierarchy progresses from component to system level consistent with ASME V&V 40 guidance."
    },
    {
